## 1. Raw Data Layer

### 1.1 Required feeds

The model requires synchronised tick-by-tick (or millisecond-level) data for the following instruments. Production requires direct exchange feeds; research can use vendor TAQ-equivalents.

| Asset | Venue | Field set |
|---|---|---|
| HYG | NYSE Arca | NBBO quotes (bid, ask, bid size, ask size, exchange flag), trades (price, size, condition codes, sale condition flag), and the official Auction Imbalance feed at open and close |
| ES1 (front E-mini S&P 500) | CME Globex MDP 3.0 | Top-of-book quote (best bid/ask, sizes), trades with aggressor side flag |
| ZN1 (front 10y Treasury Note) | CME Globex MDP 3.0 | Top-of-book quote, trades with aggressor side flag |
| CL1 (front WTI crude) | CME Globex MDP 3.0 | Top-of-book quote, trades |
| MOVE | ICE Data Services intraday MOVE feed | Index level updates (intraday published roughly every 10–60 seconds); fall back to daily close if intraday unavailable for a session |
| VIX | Cboe Global Indices feed | Index level updates (real-time, ~250ms cadence) |
| HYG indicative NAV (iNAV) | NYSE Arca iNAV feed | iNAV updates every 15 seconds during regular trading |
| HYG official NAV | NYSE Arca, end-of-day | Daily striking value at 16:00 ET |
| HYG holdings file | iShares daily basket file | Constituent-level CUSIP, weight, par |
| TRACE | FINRA TRACE BTDS | Reported trades on HYG constituents, used as a thinning indicator (not a price input) |
| Risk-free curve | DTCC SwapClear / Bloomberg | OIS curve at daily granularity |

### 1.2 Storage schema

All feeds normalise to a single Parquet partition layout, partitioned by `(symbol, year, month, day)`, sorted within partition by timestamp. A canonical row schema:

| Column | Type | Notes |
|---|---|---|
| `ts_ns` | int64 | UTC nanoseconds since epoch |
| `symbol` | string | Canonical instrument ID |
| `event_type` | enum | `quote`, `trade`, `auction`, `index_update`, `corporate_action` |
| `bid` | float64 | NaN if not a quote event |
| `ask` | float64 | NaN if not a quote event |
| `bid_sz` | int64 | NaN if not a quote event |
| `ask_sz` | int64 | NaN if not a quote event |
| `last` | float64 | Trade price; NaN otherwise |
| `last_sz` | int64 | Trade size |
| `cond_codes` | string[] | TAQ / venue condition codes |
| `seq_no` | int64 | Venue sequence number for replay verification |
| `feed_ts_ns` | int64 | Vendor receipt timestamp (for clock-skew detection) |

The `ts_ns` field is the **exchange timestamp**, not the vendor receipt timestamp. The two-timestamp design lets you reconstruct latency distributions and audit clock skew, both essential for HF correctness.

### 1.3 Clock alignment

All timestamps are stored in UTC. Display and trading-rule cutoffs (e.g., session boundaries) are evaluated in America/New_York with explicit DST handling. NYSE Arca regular session is 09:30–16:00 ET; CME futures trade nearly 24 hours but the model evaluates only during the NYSE regular session for HYG, with a "factor warm-up" window from 04:00 ET to 09:30 ET that updates fast-factor states without trading.

### 1.4 History requirements

- 4 weeks rolling tick history for the daily refit (Section 6).
- 12 months of session-level summary statistics for stress-conditioner calibration (Section 7.5).
- Approximately 100GB raw data per month for the full instrument set when stored as compressed Parquet with Zstd level 9.

