## 3. Event Stream Construction

### 3.1 Merged event stream

For online operation and EM estimation, merge all cleaned per-symbol streams into a single time-ordered stream of events keyed by `ts_ns`. For ties in `ts_ns` across symbols, order by exchange precedence (CME → NYSE Arca → ICE → Cboe), which reflects the typical fastest-to-slowest data dissemination order.

The event stream is the primary input to all downstream stages.

### 3.2 Hayashi–Yoshida overlap convention

For the offline EM step (Section 6), cross-products between asynchronous series are computed using the Hayashi–Yoshida overlap estimator. Given two series with returns $\Delta X_i$ over intervals $(\tau_{i-1}, \tau_i]$ and $\Delta Y_j$ over intervals $(\sigma_{j-1}, \sigma_j]$:

$$\widehat{\langle X, Y \rangle}_{[0,T]} = \sum_{i,j} \Delta X_i \cdot \Delta Y_j \cdot \mathbb{1}\{(\tau_{i-1}, \tau_i] \cap (\sigma_{j-1}, \sigma_j] \neq \emptyset\}$$

This estimator is unbiased and consistent for the integrated covariation under no-arbitrage assumptions on the efficient prices. **Do not** build a synchronous bar grid first — that introduces Epps-effect bias on the order of 30–50% at minute frequency for HYG–ES1 covariance.

### 3.3 Bar grids (where used)

Some downstream operations require bar-aligned data:
- Conformal calibration window scoring (Section 8) — uses 5-second bars.
- Diagnostic plots (Section 11.1) — uses 1-minute bars.
- Daily refit summary statistics — uses 1-minute bars.

When constructing bars, use the **last accepted log-mid** in the bar interval (closing-price convention); if no accepted quote occurred in the bar interval, carry forward the previous bar's value but flag the bar as "stale" and exclude from downstream estimation.

