## 11. Testing and Validation

### 11.1 In-sample diagnostics

Every refit produces a one-page diagnostic report including:
- Standardised innovations time series and ACF
- Smoothed regime probabilities over the training sample
- Realised vs. predicted basis trajectory on a held-out day
- Coverage table for conformal interval at $\alpha = 0.05, 0.10, 0.20$
- Parameter values and their changes from the previous refit (alarm if any parameter changes by more than 30% day-over-day)

### 11.2 Out-of-sample walk-forward backtest

Standard walk-forward: train on weeks $[t-4, t]$, evaluate on week $t+1$, slide. Required reporting:
- Net P&L per trade
- Sharpe ratio (annualised, assuming 252 trading days)
- Maximum drawdown
- Hit rate (fraction of profitable round-trips)
- Average holding period
- Trade count per day
- P&L attribution: basis-closure component, fast-factor drift component, residual

The backtest must include a realistic transaction cost model. For HYG: assume execution at mid for limit orders that fill, half-spread + 0.5 bps slippage for marketable orders; futures: assume tick-and-a-half slippage on marketable orders. Optimistic execution assumptions are the most common cause of false-positive backtests.

### 11.3 Statistical significance

Compute:
- Sharpe ratio standard error via Lo (2002) corrected formula accounting for return autocorrelation.
- Probabilistic Sharpe ratio and Deflated Sharpe ratio (Bailey & López de Prado 2014) — particularly important here because the parameter space is large and overfitting risk is real.
- Strategy-vs-benchmark t-statistic with HAC standard errors.

A live deployment recommendation requires DSR > 0.95.

### 11.4 Stress-period evaluation

Specifically backtest performance through:
- March 2020 (COVID dislocation)
- October 2008 (peak crisis — synthetic since HYG was newer)
- August 2011 (US downgrade)
- December 2018 (Q4 risk-off)
- March 2023 (regional banking stress)

Required: model should *not lose money* during these periods, even if it makes none. A model that trades through stress is more dangerous than one that sits out — track regime-recognition lag (time from objective regime change to $\pi(S) > 0.5$); target lag below 60 seconds.

### 11.5 Adversarial backtests

- Permute the basis residual and check that the model produces near-zero P&L (sanity check on overfitting).
- Replace one fast factor with a synthetic Brownian motion of matched volatility and verify the model assigns near-zero loading after EM (specification check).
- Simulate iNAV staleness shocks (jump iNAV by $\pm 0.5\%$) and verify the model does not generate spurious signals (robustness check).

### 11.6 Live shadow run

Before any capital allocation, run the model in shadow mode for 30 trading days, recording all signals and *paper* P&L. Compare to backtest expectations. Live shadow Sharpe should be within 1 std-dev of backtest Sharpe; large divergences indicate model–reality mismatch in microstructure or execution assumptions.

